caption: Holy Batman Benedict! There’s a reason this place boasts “Best Breakfast in Chicago!” Just steps off the waterfront, near the Navy Pier, this adorable cafe is everything you would wish for on a cold Chicago morning. Hot coffee, with frequent refills, Texas sized portions (for this Dallas girl) of California Benedict and Red Velvet French Toast. (Warning- bring your insulin!) The perfect place to grab a hearty morning meal or just a coffee on the run in the Windy City
Loved it! The attention was excellent! And the food was next level delicious... I had the egg burrito with chorizo and I'm craving it 24/7 since I left Chicago... OMG! A must!

I brought my step mom there when she was in visiting from out of state. We have had breakfast there at least 8 times during the summer and were never disappointed with the food or the service.

We chose this place for our weekend brunch after it was recommended by one of the bartenders we met in town. We were seated immediately and welcomed by a waitress. Mimosas were great but food was just average and the restaurant seemed a bit dirty. Dust in bathroom, kitchen didn’t look organized or clean as I passed, etc. Eclectic menu but probably wouldn’t recommend to anyone.

The post-quarantine reopning has definitely affected their service, and they need to restructure. The kitchen is working at full throttle trying to keep up with online orders for delivery and carry-out but forgot about the diners in-house.  After checking in on Yelp, the hostess did not have an estimated time on when my party would be seated. Once seated 20 minutes after, the server took our full order and we waited a long time before even receiving our drinks (1 singular mimosa carafe and 1 latte). When our latte got to our table it was obvious it was sitting at the bar for some time; it was flat and tasted burnt.  In addition to getting 2 things wrong from our order, the crabcake benedict tasted 2 weeks old with an obvious funk to the crab.  Stick with just the online orders; they're not ready to back to regular dinning.

The food and drinks here were awesome there was a bit of a wait but well worth it for the food.

The server was great, couldn’t be happier. Awesome staff. The mimosa pitcher was great. They have cholula. Another bonus point. However, the kitchen doesn’t modify food at all and this is a trend I’m noticing in breakfast restaurants that I need to die, or at least give it the rating it deserves, 3-stars. My wife wanted a Lox bagel and to sub out the cream cheese for an avocado. I totally understand the upcharge. However, they won’t put it on the bagel because the kitchen doesn’t do modifications. They’ll charge you for the avocado and deliver it on the side. At the point you are re-building your own Lox bagel, which is actually more work than starting from scratch, what is the point of going to a restaurant where a kitchen makes your food and delivers it to you? Also, if the kitchens have discovered that this makes their food come out lighting fast with this methodology, maybe I’d understand.  But no, the lead time on the food was average to probably slow, and it wasn’t overly impressive in quality or presentation.  I think we’ll hit the grocery store next time instead. They’re lucky their staff is so stellar or they’d get worse than 3 stars.

I really wanted to like this place. I'm new in the neighborhood and was really hoping this would be my new brunch spot. The food quality and taste was good, but not up to the price point. The serving size was not up to the price point. Either of these on their own isn't a problem, but both at the same time is a bummer. From the hostess to our waitress, to the busser - not a single person smiled. Everyone seemed to be unhappy to be there. I ordered a benedict with veggie bacon. It was just a few strips of dry Morning Star Farms. My wife and I both ordered coffee. It was something like $3.95 for a bottomless cup of coffee. Neither of us ever got a refill or warm up. Maybe things were just off this day. It can happen. We'll try again.

Judging by her posture and tone, we didn’t want to continue speaking to her so we asked to speak to the manager. She informed us that the manager will probably say the same thing that she stated, and she walked away hastefully. We were so discontented with her customer service, that we offered to pay for the drinks and leave. In brief, we did end up moving our table thanks to our waiter, Josh. He was attentive and really tried to accommodate us. However, the experience we had speaking to the host (Caroline) was distasteful. As a result of that, we will not be returning. At 2:30pm we had all arrived and began to order and noticed that there was nets/flies on the wall— not very noticeable but disturbing. We asked the hostess if we can move seats and she gave horrible attitude and said NO- flat out! We showed her the flies right above our head and she shrugged it off, we asked for a manager and she informed us the manager did not approve us to move because they close at 3pm. Again, we had been there since 2pm and ready to order at 2:30pm. After the hostess continue to be rude, our friend spoke with a manager who was able to RECTIFY the situation and we truly appreciate him and the waiter who was a gentleman. Please be aware, of Caroline or Carolina who is is rude and has horrible customer service that will lead to this business losing customers.

Kanela could have been a great experience. Having just landed in Chicago, my partner and I were looking for a well-reviewed breakfast joint near Lakeshore, and Kanela’s menu and reviews seemed promising. We were incredibly excited to enjoy some delicious French toast and waffles, but the experience started off rough when the waitress, Kristin, was standoffish about a simple question (can I get syrup, please?). We placed our order, and about 15 minutes later, the butter for our food arrived. About 20 minutes after that, our food showed up, and it was completely room temp. Additionally, the pork sausage we ordered wasn’t there at all. When we pointed out that our food was cold, Kristin was again very rude, offered no apology, and just very abruptly said “do you want another?” multiple times. We also asked about our sausage, after giving up on the cold food, and she said she brought our other food out while the sausage was cooking because it takes longer. Now, it’s one thing to say you forgot it, but it’s another to lie, because we watched our food sit there, and the sausage was the only hot item we got because it was finished about 10 minutes after the rest of our food.  Had the staff been friendly, or the food even remotely warm, this would have been a great place, and exactly what we had hoped. Unfortunately, with Kristin at the frontlines and cold food behind her, it fell extremely short.

The menu is so versatile with many different healthy and comfort food options (i.e. Brussels sprouts, burgers, chicken and waffles, classic pancakes, burgers, chilaquilles, unique salads). a local chain with a few locations around Chicago (Streeterville, Old Town, Andersonville, Lakeview, Wicker Park and Ukrainian Village). I went to the Streeterville location that's close to Navy Pier but a little off the beaten path, so I would suspect it doesn't get too touristy, which is ideal for me. the atmosphere was nice. family friendly. not too hipster. the food was good. I ordered potato pancakes with a side of apple chicken sausage. the sausage was tasty and browned just right. the potato pancakes were really dense - one more so than the other - but the flavor was really good. my boyfriend had the corned beef hash, with nice big chunks of corned beef and Brussels sprouts mixed with nice chunks of potatoes. I liked it and he seemed to enjoy it - he cleaned the plate. he also said the coffee was really good. I don't drink coffee so you'll have to take his word for it.  there were plenty of menu options, including several vegetarian and vegan options. overall it was a solid restaurant. I will add it to my list of go-to spots when I'm in Chicago.
